{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6aac0d00-58f0-4f80-8033-2978776acdaa","content":"The process isn't on this machine, but here's how to detect the runtime and configure dumps on your server:\n\n### 1. Detect CoreCLR vs NativeAOT\n\n```bash\n# Method A: Check for libcoreclr in loaded libraries\ncat /proc/12345/maps | grep -q libcoreclr && echo \"CoreCLR\" || echo \"Likely NativeAOT\"\n\n# Method B: Check if createdump exists alongside the binary\nEXE=$(readlink -f /proc/12345/exe)\nls \"$(dirname \"$EXE\")\"/createdump 2>/dev/null && echo \"CoreCLR\" || echo \"Likely NativeAOT\"\n\n# Method C: Check for the runtime config file\nls \"$(dirname \"$(readlink -f /proc/12345/exe)\")\"/*.runtimeconfig.json 2>/dev/null\n# NativeAOT apps typically don't ship this file\n```\n\n### 2a. Configure dumps — CoreCLR\n\nCoreCLR has its own built-in dump mechanism via environment variables:\n\n```bash\n# Set these before launching the app (e.g., in your systemd unit or shell):\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1          # Enable automatic dumps on crash\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4            # 4 = Full heap dump (1=Mini, 2=WithHeap, 3=Triage, 4=Full)\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/var/dumps/coredump.%p.%t  # %p=PID, %t=timestamp\n```\n\nOr in a **systemd unit file**:\n```ini\n[Service]\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/var/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\n```\n\n### 2b. Configure dumps — NativeAOT\n\nNativeAOT doesn't have `createdump`; it relies on the **kernel's core dump** mechanism:\n\n```bash\n# 1. Enable core dumps (no size limit)\nulimit -c unlimited\n\n# 2. Configure the kernel core pattern\necho '/var/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n\n# To persist across reboots:\necho 'kernel.core_pattern=/var/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /etc/sysctl.d/90-coredump.conf\nsudo sysctl --system\n```\n\nIf using **systemd-coredump** (common on modern distros):\n```bash\n# Check if systemd-coredump is active\ncat /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n# If it shows \"|/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-coredump ...\", dumps go to /var/lib/systemd/coredump/\n# List them with:\ncoredumpctl list\n```\n\n### 3. Verify the dump directory exists\n\n```bash\nsudo mkdir -p /var/dumps\nsudo chmod 1777 /var/dumps\n```\n\n**TL;DR:** Run the `grep libcoreclr` check first. If CoreCLR → use the `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` env vars. If NativeAOT → configure kernel core dumps via `core_pattern` + `ulimit -c unlimited`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c2dc0100-9aee-4f14-858b-a35efa79f622","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist on this machine, which makes sense — this is a generic workspace, not the user's server. I should give them guidance on how to determine the runtime and configure dumps, rather than trying to run commands here.\n\nLet me provide a comprehensive answer with the detection techniques and configuration for both runtimes.","outputTokens":925,"requestId":"AC0C:2E3AFD:141D241:169C81D:6A0672CE"},"id":"9f13074e-25b6-45cd-b6e7-0364f3759c7f","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:12:01.214Z","parentId":"120ea388-8b36-4475-a276-b27591f87891"}
